metadata.name: Limina #49
metadata.description:
Limina is a study of the fine line between order and chaos.

Each piece of the collection is made up of just one or two lines. These lines are defined by thousands of points that are chosen, one by one, by a simple algorithm moving across the canvas. What arises from that simple concept is a surprising variety of intricate patterns, accidental symmetries and traces of order in chaotic structures. 

Limina is a meditation on the concept of emergence, a concept that lies at the heart of generative art. The algorithm that defines the core of the series is only capable of making one simple choice: left, right, up or down? As it moves across the canvas, it leaves a trace of points that are connected by a curve. The order in which these points are chosen and the tightness of the curve connecting them is what creates the visual diversity of Limina. As these values fluctuate, symmetries emerge and break down again, forms, patterns and ornaments are created and combined to form both complex structures and simple abstractions. 

Limina shows the potential of minimalist generative concepts to generate visually dense and unexpected results. 

Press 's' to save your image.

metadata.name: Bored in Math Class #75
metadata.description:
Bored in Math Class is a project all about exploring grids. Using grids is common in generative art, and I wanted to see how far I could push this simple technique. I integrated an irregular square packing algorithm described by Gorilla Sun on one of his blog posts to give the compositions more variety rather than just having a uniform grid. I explored a bunch of different ideas and repurposed some old code to generate patterns inside each square. Many of the patterns can be layered on top of each other to make the composition even more interesting. I decided to call it "Bored in Math Class" because it has a playful feel and the grids remind me of graph paper that I would doodle on when I was bored [in math class of course].

There are 10 color palettes, 5 different types of grids, and 8 types of patterns (though they can be layered to create more).

Press 'p' while on Live View to save a high quality (4000x4000) png of the canvas.

Created using p5.js

Licensed under CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Ongemak #77
metadata.description:
Wabi-sabi (侘寂): appreciate impermanence and imperfection

There is little chance of a 'perfect' work of art. The small imperfections require reflection. 

The variation and randomness give the work some asymmetry, common in wabi-sabi esthetics. Because of a limited color palette and the simple shapes used, the works keep their simplicity (another principle of wabi-sabi). The noisy texture gives it some roughness, indeed again a core principle of wabi-sabi. 

The colors are reminiscent of the 70s and 80s. Some think that everything was better in the past. The trick is to enjoy the moment.

Thinking about impermanence is sometimes uncomfortable, 'ongemak' in Dutch, but also valuable.

metadata.name: Onward, to Hy Breasail #21
metadata.description:
Hy Breasail was an island that only existed on the antique maps.
According to belief, there was a fantastic island that roamed the ocean and was completely covered in mists. Every seven years, the mists dissipated and the land could be seen by human eyes, but never reached.

With this project, I wanted to remember this history, creating maps that never existed before, a paper cartography, where sometimes it is blurred or glitched, because of the fog that haunts the island.

This project have 2 predominant colors + 2 blendModes, wich can invert the colors or change, a total of 4 colors pallettes.

It takes a little time to render completely (10 seconds aprox.), but after it has rendered all the base art, the textures are loaded.

Styles can vary from grids, horizontal divisions, vertical divisions, and the clean aspect, without glitching.


- open in live view for a better experience.


This is a project in p5.js

Omar Lobato Neto,
02/06/2022.

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #11
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.
